        "id": 1013536
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-06T15:06:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "To avoid doubling the API when we allow non-pure functions, we could have this marker pass as a first argument, for instance.\n\ncue.NewFunc2(cue.Pure, arg0, arg1)\n\nor even\n\ncue.NewFunc2(arg0, arg1, cue.Pure(true))",
      "revId": "065668779bc865ca3775c5b2702e4b079a79cf10",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9766cc9a_5dbfbc65",
        "filename": "designs/4293-user-functions-and-validators.md",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 204,
      "author": {
        "id": 1007275
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-13T18:03:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "FWIW my gut feeling here is that as this is CUE, and CUE is known as a side-effect-free language, that there\u0027s no real need to require the term \"pure\" to be provided explicitly. That is, I\u0027d probably go for:\n\n    cue.NewFunc(f)\n\nand if/when we add support for impure functions, we could add that as an option:\n\n    cue.NewFunc(f, cue.Impure())\n\nI suspect there might well be other options that pertain to impurity, such as what kind of call semantics are required (e.g. at-least-once), so having things this way around makes sense to me.\n\nThis also means that if we decide to use some other mechanism for impure functions in the future, this API itself stays clean.\n\n\u003e cue.NewFunc2(arg0, arg1, cue.Pure(true))\n\nOne thing I\u0027d mention about that approach is that it\u0027s almost invariable about the function option pattern that it\u0027s OK to omit all the options and get default values. If we were to choose a default value, ISTM that the most obvious default would be for purity, which would align with my thoughts above.",
      "parentUuid": "b8d1f258_53a45d4b",
      "revId": "065668779bc865ca3775c5b2702e4b079a79cf10",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
